    "difficulty": "hard",
    "stem": "A widower names his three adult children as beneficiaries of his life insurance policy “per stirpes.” One child dies before the insured, leaving two children of her own. When the insured later dies, how will the death benefit ordinarily be distributed under a per stirpes designation?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "The two surviving children split the entire death benefit equally, and the deceased child's descendants receive nothing."
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "The death benefit is paid entirely to the estate of the child who died first."
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Each surviving child receives one-third, and the deceased child's one-third share passes equally to that child's descendants."
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "All four grandchildren and children share the proceeds equally per capita."
      }
    ],
    "correct_answer": "C",
    "correct_explanation": "A per stirpes designation means that each branch of the family receives the share that the deceased beneficiary would have taken. Here, each of the insured's three children represents one branch. The two living children each receive one-third, and the deceased child's one-third share passes to that child's descendants equally.",
    "wrong_explanations": {
      "A": "That result would be more consistent with having no contingent treatment for the deceased beneficiary's line, not a per stirpes designation.",
      "B": "A per stirpes designation passes the share down the deceased beneficiary's line rather than paying it to the deceased beneficiary's estate by default.",
      "D": "Equal sharing among all descendants regardless of branch would be a per capita concept, not per stirpes."
    },
